i lost an afternoon to this one...  if  the files being processed by the FileService class (for processing local mail files) are not readable/writable/deletable, in a default config the scanner ignores them and produces no output.  as far as i could tell the service wasn't even running based on the logfile contents.

after cranking up the debugging i got more information that it was actually doing something:

2009-06-18 15:10:23,796 JiraQuartzScheduler_Worker-2 DEBUG [atlassian.jira.service.ServiceRunner] Running Service [Container: com.atlassian.jira.service.services.file.FileService  delay [60000ms]]
2009-06-18 15:10:23,796 JiraQuartzScheduler_Worker-2 DEBUG [service.services.file.FileService] Getting files in directory: /opt/jira/mail/ithelp

but that's still not incredibly helpful.  fortunately the source for this is available so i could take a peek:

            for (int i = 0; i < files.length; i++)
            {
                File file = files[i];

                // it needs to be a file, and we need to be able to read it and then delete it
                if (file.isFile() && file.canRead() && file.canWrite())
                {
                    log.debug("Trying to parse file: " + file.getAbsolutePath());
                    try
                    {
                        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(file);
                        Message message = new MimeMessage(null, fis);
                        boolean delete = getHandler().handleMessage(message);
                        fis.close();
                        if (delete)
                        {
                            log.info("Deleting file: " + file.getAbsolutePath());
                            file.delete();
                        }
                    }
                    catch (FileNotFoundException e)
                    {
                        // this shouldn't happen
                        log.error("File not found when it should be, are two FileServices running?", e);
                    }
                    catch (MessagingException e)
                    {
                        log.error("Messaging exception: " + e, e);
                    }
                    catch (Throwable t)
                    {
                        log.error("Throwable: " + t, t);
                    }
                }
            }

it seems that there really ought to be an  "else { log.warn("Unable to read/write/delete file: " + file.getAbsolutePath()); }" in there as opposed to silently continuing.

in our case we had a procmail recipe that was mistakenly delivering some files with root ownership instead of the targeted user.

